9/2: TEST 38:
Listening:
Reading:
Writing:
The line graph illustrates changes in the weekly consumption of four types of meat and fish in a European country between 1979 and 2004, measured in grams per person.

Overall, chicken consumption rose steadily to become the most popular by the end of the period, while beef and lamb showed clear downward trends. 
Fish, by contrast, remained the least consumed food throughout and declined only slightly.

At the beginning, beef was the most widely eaten meat at just over 200 grams per person per week, despite some fluctuations in the early 1980s. However, its consumption fell markedly after the late 1980s, dropping to a little above 100 grams by 2004. 
Lamb followed a similar but less dramatic pattern, decreasing from around 150 grams at the start to roughly 60 grams at the end.

In contrast, chicken intake increased consistently over the 25-year period. Starting at about 150 grams per week, it overtook beef around 1990 and continued to rise, reaching approximately 250 grams by 2004. 
Fish consumption was much lower throughout, beginning at around 60 grams and gradually declining to just over 40 grams per person per week.
