Quest 1:
The line graph illustrates the proportions of four types of household waste that were recycled in a city during the period between 1992 and 2002.
Overall, recycling rates of paper, glass and cans had an uptrend over the period, while plastic remained the least recycled material throughout the surveyed period.
At first, glass was the most recycled material at just over 18% in 1992 and it demonstrated a steady surge to over 48% in 2002. Paper followed a similar but less dramatic pattern, increasing from around 15% to around 38% in the end.
In contract, cans decreased from over 18% in 1992 to 15% in 1997, but it again raised up to over 28% in 2002.
Plastic was much lower throughout, begining at around 10% and presented a stable pattern in 1997 and 2002, at over 12%.

Quest 2:
The given graph illustrates the amount of visits to a community website during its first and second years of operation.
Overall, the figures of visits in first year tended to increase . Meanwhile, the second year of use showed a down trend.  
At the begining, in the first year, the number of visits rose steadily from July, starting at around 25,000, and reached a peak of approximately 40,000 in October. Although there was a slight decline in November and December, visits increased again to just over 40,000 in February.
After that, a downward trend was observed, with figures falling to about 15,000 in April before rising again to nearly 38,000 in June.
In contrast, the second year showed consistently lower numbers. Visits generally fluctuated between 10,000 and 20,000, peaking at around 21,000 in January. The lowest point was seen in April, at approximately 7,000 visits, followed by a modest recovery towards June.

Quest 4:
The line graph illustrates changes in the total number of four types of fish worldwide between 1982 and 2007.
Overall, Atlantic cod and yellowfin tuna showed a down trend over the period, while haddock and swordfish remained relatively stable. Among the four species, swordfish was consistently the least numerous.
At the start, Atlantic cod had the highest number, at just over 220,000 in 1982. Although it fell to around 150,000 in 1992, it rose slightly later before dropping again to about 135,000 in 2007.
By contrast, yellowfin tuna increased from about 150,000 to nearly 200,000 in 1992. After that, its number went down steadily and reached around 100,000 at the end.
Meanwhile, haddock increased slowly from about 70,000 to just over 75,000, while swordfish stayed low at around 10,000 throughout.

Quest 5:
The given graph show the mean time people in different age groups in New Zealand spent on two leisure activities per day.
Overall, time spent on reading increased with age, while listening to music showed a downward trend over the period.
At the beginning, people aged 14–24 spent the least time on reading, at about 20 minutes per day. This figure rose gradually in older groups, reaching around 35 minutes for those aged 25–32 and about 45–50 minutes among people aged 33–55. The highest amount was seen in the 56–65+ group, at roughly 70 minutes.
In contrast, listening to music showed the opposite pattern. The youngest group spent the most time, at nearly 80 minutes per day. The figure then fell to about 60 minutes in the 25–32 group and reached around 45 minutes among those aged 33–42. After that, it increased again to about 75 minutes in the oldest group.

Quest 6:
The line graph show the feelings of full-time and part-time students about the services of a university library.
Overall, satisfaction with opening hours was high, while opinions about IT support showed a downward trend among part-time students compared with full-time students.
For IT support, most full-time students were happy, with 55% very satisfied and 32% quite satisfied. Only 12% were not satisfied. In contrast, part-time students were less positive, as the largest group (45%) were not satisfied at all, while only 20% were very satisfied.
Regarding opening hours, both groups gave positive opinions. Among full-time students, almost all were satisfied, with 67% very satisfied. Similarly, most part-time students were happy, as 72% reported being very satisfied and only a small number were unhappy

quest 7:
The table compares the proportions of women in parliament and in management positions in five countries in 2000.
Overall, the figures for women in management had an uptrend, while the percentages of women in parliament showed a downward trend in five countries.
In terms of parliament, Norway ranked first, with 36% of seats held by women, followed by Canada at 28%. Much lower figures were recorded in Trinidad and Tobago (19%) and Italy (10%), while Uruguay had the lowest proportion, at just 8%.
By contrast, the percentages of women in management were higher across all countries. Italy had the highest figure, at 54%, closely followed by Norway with 52%. Canada and Uruguay both stood at 37%, whereas Trinidad and Tobago recorded 40%.

Quest 8:
The give graph compare how men and women in the UK spent time on unpaid activities in 2008, measured in minutes per day.
Overall, time spent by women on household work showed an upward trend, while men spent more time on leisure activities, which showed a higher level rather than a downward trend compared with women.
According to the table, men spent more time on TV, video and radio (137 minutes) than women (118 minutes). Time spent on reading was almost the same for both genders, at around 18–19 minutes, while men spent slightly more time on sport.
The bar chart shows clear differences in household tasks. Women spent much more time on cooking and washing, at about 75 minutes, compared with around 30 minutes for men. Women also spent more time on shopping and clothes washing, while men spent more time on repair work.

Quest 10:
The line graph shows the amount of users of fixed telephone lines and mobile phone networks in Africa during the period between 1994 and 2004.
Overall, the use of mobile phones showed a strong upward trend, while fixed telephone lines had a slow upward trend over the period.
At the begining, fixed telephone lines were used by about 1.7 people per 100, whereas mobile phones were almost unused, at around 0.06. The number of fixed-line users increased gradually, reaching just over 3 per 100 people by 2004.
By contrast, mobile phone use rose much faster. After a slow increase in the late 1990s, it grew sharply from 1999, overtook fixed lines in the early 2000s, and reached nearly 9 users per 100 people at the end of the period.

quest 11:
The line graph depicts the proportions of people working in five industries in Australia from 1962 to 2012.
Overall, employment in the service sector showed an upward trend, while the figures for manufacturing, agriculture and other industries had a downtrend over the period.
At the begining, Services was the highest workforce, started at just over 51% in 1962 and it steadily increased to 80% in 2012.
However, construction and Mining stayed extremely low, each remain below 10% during the period.
In contract, Manufacturing decreased over the 50-year period. starting with over 26% , and it continued to dropping to 10% in 2012.
Adriculture followed a similar but less pattern, falling from 10% to over 5% over the period.

Quest 12:
The bar chart illustrates the proportion of people living in urban areas in different regions of the world in 1950 and 2000, with a projection for 2030.
Overall, the proportion of urban residents showed an upward trend over time. Latin America had the highest level of urbanisation throughout the period, while Africa and Asia remained less urbanised despite significant growth.
At the beginning of the period in 1950, Latin America was the most urbanised region, with about 40% of its population living in cities. The global average stood at approximately 30%. In contrast, Africa and Asia had much lower figures, at around 10% and just over 10% respectively.
By contrast, in 2000 and 2030, the percentages increased in every region. Latin America rose to about 70% in 2000 and is expected to reach 80% in 2030. The world figure also increased to nearly 50% and is predicted to reach around 60%. Although Africa and Asia started lower, both are expected to grow to more than 50% by 2030.

Quest 13: 
The table depicts the amountof adults and children who took part in a wildlife survey in Britain fromm 2001 to 2009.
Overall, the total number of people taking part in the wildlife survey showed an upward trend, despite some small changes in the middle years. While the number of adults experienced a slight downward trend towards the end of the period.
At the beginning, in 2001, a total of 48,000 people took part in the survey. Most of them were adults, at 36,000, while only 12,000 were children. In 2003, the total number increased greatly to 248,000, mainly because adult participation rose to 212,000.
By contrast, in the later years, participation reached much higher levels. In 2005 and 2007, the total number stayed stable at just over 360,000, with adults remaining the main group. However, in 2009, the number of children increased dramatically to 270,000, equal to the number of adults, which led to the highest total figure of 540,000.

Quest 14:
The line graph depicts the cost of bananas in four countries, namely Japan, France, Germany and the USA, between 1996 and 2004.
Overall, the cost of bananas in Japan and Germany followed an upward trend , although Japan had large changes and Germany experienced a short downward trend. France remained stable, while the USA had almost no upward.
At the beginning of the period, banana costs in Japan and France were about 2 dollars per kilogram. Germany started lower, at around 1.5 dollars, while the USA had the lowest cost, at about 1 dollar. During the late 1990s, costs in Japan rose sharply, while Germany saw a slight downward trend.
By contrast, in the later years, banana costs in Japan continued to fluctuate and ended at around 2.5 dollars in 2004. Germany increased gradually to nearly 2 dollars before falling slightly. France showed small changes but stayed close to 2 dollars, whereas the cost in the USA remained almost unchanged throughout the period.

Quest 15:
The bar charts depicts the proportions of men and women aged 60–64 who were in employment in Belgium, the USA, Japan and Indonesia between 1970 and 2000.
Overall, employment rates for both men and women showed a clear downward trend in all four countries between 1970 and 2000. Despite this decline, men consistently had higher employment levels than women in both years.
At the beginning, in 1970, employment rates for men were high in every country, reaching over 80% in the USA and Indonesia. Belgium and Japan also recorded figures of around 75–80%. For women, the USA had the highest rate at nearly 80%, while Japan had the lowest at just over 50%.
By contrast, in 2000, employment levels were much lower. Male employment fell to about 50% in Belgium and around 60–75% elsewhere. Female employment decreased more sharply, particularly in Belgium, where it dropped to below 10%, while the other countries remained between roughly 45% and 60%.
